article.description: Sixth-ranked Minnesota remained the only unbeaten team in the country, getting 15 points from Janel McCarville in a 74-59 victory Thursday night over Illinois.
article.headline: Gophers' McCarville sinks 15 points
article.linkText: No. 6 Minnesota drops Illinois, remains undefeated
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Sixth-ranked Minnesota remained the only
unbeaten team in the country Thursday, but the Gophers took an
unfamiliar route to get there.

The Gophers, who usually lean on stars Lindsay Whalen and Janel
McCarville for the bulk of their scoring, got 24 points from their
freshmen reserves in a 74-59 victory over Illinois.

Whalen, who is second in the nation in scoring at 23 points a
game, posted a season-low 12 points on only 11 shots, while
McCarville came up just shy of her season average with 15 points.
But the Gophers (15-0, 4-0 Big Ten) got 11 points from senior
Kadidja Andersson and their trio of freshmen helped the bench
outscore Illinois' reserves 24-11.

"We've been riding Janel and Lindsay's backs all year,"
Minnesota coach Pam Borton said. "But this is what's going to make
us a better team, what happened here tonight."

Whalen didn't get on the board until six minutes remained in the
first half, but the Gophers already held a 24-12 lead when she
converted on a driving reverse layup.

"In the last two weeks we've talked about how we've got to have
a lot of people stepping up and scoring, and tonight proved we can
do that," Whalen said. "When teams put two people on Janel, it
opens things up for other players."

Minnesota got big contributions from each of its freshman to
make up for Whalen's early scoring drought. Liz Podominick had six
straight points, Kelly Roysland scored on a drive and a 3-pointer
and Jamie Broback hit on back-to-back possessions as Minnesota took
a 40-20 halftime lead.

"You can't come in here and think you're just going to nail
down one player," Illinois coach Theresa Grentz said. "I admire
talented people and that's a talented team that I enjoy watching."

Angelina Williams led Illinois (7-9, 1-4) with 21 points, while
Cindy Dallas added 12 points and 12 rebounds and Tiffanie Guthrie
chipped in with 10 points.

McCarville's 11 rebounds helped Minnesota to a 40-33 advantage
on the boards against the Big Ten's top rebounding team.

Williams scored 10 points on a series of jump shots in a
four-minute span early in the second half, and foul trouble dogged
Minnesota as the Illini wouldn't let the Gophers pull away. Both
McCarville and Whalen picked up their fourth fouls midway through
the second half and sat out four minutes as Illinois closed the gap
to 63-50 with 5:59 to play.

But Andersson scored six points and fed Shannon Schonrock for a
driving baseline layup as the Gophers regained control at 70-50
with less than four minutes to play.

"I felt like we were kind of losing energy, and it was my
responsibility to get that energy going," Andersson said. "We
can't just depend on Lindsay and (McCarville) to do all the scoring
for us. Other people have to step up."

The Gophers now face their toughest stretch of the season, with
games at No. 10 Purdue on Sunday and No. 8 Penn State on Thursday.
After a week in which three of the nation's top five teams lost,
Minnesota knows it can't afford to think too much about its lofty
ranking.

"We respect every team in the Big Ten. We talk about seizing
the moment, not being complacent and not taking things for
granted," Borton said. "This week has shown that you can lose on
any given night if you're not focused. It can be gone, just like
that."
